\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This script can be link to the mousewheel (wit shift for example), to trigger the horizontal zoom, but with an adaptative beheviour, that zooms slowly when the view is large, and quickly if the view is tight.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The strenght of the effect can be modified at the beginning of the script\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This script cleans selected items of useless sustain pedal CC64 (between 1 and 126) and also redundant 0 or 127 values\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This script adjusts notes lengths so that they do not overlap.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab It respects chords, i.e. notes that starts around the same time (within a time threshold)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Can be used on selected items in the arrange view, or selected notes in the MIDI editor\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This script displays smoothly scrolling lyrics in a separate window.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Lyrics are imported from a TEXT file (one sentence per line, empty lines are excluded) in the form of media items in a dedicated lyrics track, named "Lyrics" (not case sensitive)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If not existing, this track is automaticaly created.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab By default, the TEXT file browser points in the project directory.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab During import, lyrics can be added at the end of the existing lyrics as new items, or can replace the existing ones.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab After import, you can move and resize items to synchronize currently displayed lyrics with the underlying music.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The currently displayed lyric lines depend on the position of the edit or play cursor on the timeline.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab By default, the size of the lyrics window becomes bigger when the project is playing, to easily read the lyrics from your recording position, far from the screen.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab On the contrary, when the project is stopped, the window size is reduced to allow easy editing of the tracks underneath.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can disable this behaviour with the "auto resize" options, if you want.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can also change the fonts sizes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can change the colors of lines, depending on their status (reading, preparing, offline)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can choose how many lines you want to see before of after the current one.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can change the position and size of the window in both playing/stopped modes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab You can change the default duration of a lyric item, and the default duration of the gap between lyric items.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab All these choices/options are memorized for the next reaper session.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Note that the first track called "Lyrics" is taken into account, so you can have several tracks scalled "Lyrics"; just put the active one in the upper position.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab To avoid useless cpu work, note that, if you modify the lyric track during playback, the display is not updated. you have to stop and resume playback to refresh the lyrics.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Use the context menu (mouse right click).\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This script reloads the current project, without saving it (so take care...)\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This script scales notes velocities between min and max values (that can be outside the 0..127 range)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Can be used on selected items in the arrange view, or selected notes in the MIDI editor\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This script transposes selected items by a number of semitones\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Can be used on selected items in the arrange view, or selected notes in the MIDI editor\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab This script trims selected items, deleting invisible parts (audio or midi)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Useful to clean unused audio parts, and reduced audio files sizes.\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Compress MIDI notes velocities, with an autogain feature that keeps the maximum velocity to 127.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Change the sensitivity of the MIDI input, i.e. the relation between keyboard touch and velocity. Values : 0-4:light touch, 5: normal touch, 6-9:heavy touch, 10: constant touch\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Transpose MIDI notes of a project by semitones. One instance of this plugin should be added to the master track. Then you have to add a "MIDI Transpose Track" plugin on every MIDI track you want to transpose. This solution makes it easy to transpose a whole MIDI project with one slider.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Transpose MIDI notes of a track by semitones. The Track Transpose value only affects the current track, but can be combined with the Project Transpose value, shared by all instances of this plugin in the project, and defined in the "MIDI Transpose Project" plugin added to the master track.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Change the gain of the side channel while MS encoding/decoding, to emphasize/reequilibrate the effect on the side channel of any MS compliant plugin applied to the signal. Adapted from an original idea of Dan Worall (all credits to him !) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dD6_Bajj2DI Choose an ID common to a unique encoder/decoder chain, to link both ionstances together and share the side boost value in realtime. Default side boost value is +6dB (as advised by DW). For classical MS encoding, use 0dB.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Change the gain of the side channel while MS encoding/decoding, to emphasize/reequilibrate the effect on the side channel of any MS compliant plugin applied to the signal. Adapted from an original idea of Dan Worall (all credits to him !) https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dD6_Bajj2DI Choose an ID common to a unique encoder/decoder chain, to link both ionstances together and share the side boost value in realtime. Default side boost value is +6dB (as advised by DW). For classical MS encoding, use 0dB.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A simple plugin that adds or removes gain to the audio signal.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A simple plugin that adds or removes gain to the audio signal, but changing the resulting gain smoothly if the target value changes rapidly. The "smoothness" of the effect can be adjusted\par}
}

